\":\"Cam04\",\"targets\":3},{\"name\":\"Cam05\",\"targets\":4},{\"name\":\"Cam06\",\"targets\":5},{\"name\":\"Cam07\",\"targets\":6},{\"name\":\"Cam08\",\"targets\":7},{\"name\":\"Cam09\",\"targets\":8},{\"name\":\"Cam10\",\"targets\":9}],\"order\":[],\"orderClasses\":false,\"lengthMenu\":[10,15,25,50,100]}},\"evals\":[],\"jsHooks\":[]}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n</details>\n\nTo calculate the species richness, the total number of species observed in each ejido was added for the Project Extent, while excluding any species that was found outside of the tropical/sub-tropical dry forests.\n\n## Avian Species Richness\n\nAt each point, the geographical coordinates, point number, time, species observed/heard, number of individuals per species, distance and observation height were taken. Another aspect to mention, in some points more transects were made and in others less, due to the conditions of the terrain and surface of the area. The recorded species were identified using binoculars (8x42) and the field guide “Go out and bird Yucatán” (2014) and the Merlin application (The Cornell Lab).\n\nEach coordinate for point counts (observation points) was included in the raw data and were cross referenced with the location of each coordinate and the associated functional group. Any point and corresponding data was excluded if it was not located in the Tropical/Sub-tropical dry forests, as seen in [Table 9](#table9).\n\n<details>\n\n<summary>Table 9. Classification per Field Data Plot</summary>\n\n::: {#table9}\n:::\n\n::: terra-table-title\nTable 9. Classification per Field Data Plot\n:::\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<div class=\"datatables html-widget html-fill-item\" id=\"htmlwidget-3302909d2e5b0f889932\" style=\"width:100%;height:auto;\"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-3302909d2e5b0f889932\">{\"x\":{\"filter\":\"none\",\"vertical\":false,\"data\":[[105,201],[\"1.5. Forest Subtropical/tropical dry\",\"2.1. Savanna - Dry\"]],\"container\":\"<table class=\\\"stripe hover compact\\\">\\n  <thead>\\n    <tr>\\n      <th>IUCN_NatFrame<\\/th>\\n      <th>Habitat type<\\/th>\\n    <\\/tr>\\n  <\\/thead>\\n<\\/table>\",\"options\":{\"paging\":false,\"searching\":false,\"pageLength\":15,\"scrollX\":true,\"autoWidth\":true,\"columnDefs\":[{\"className\":\"dt-right\",\"targets\":0},{\"name\":\"IUCN_NatFrame\",\"targets\":0},{\"name\":\"Habitat type\",\"targets\":1}],\"order\":[],\"orderClasses\":false,\"lengthMenu\":[10,15,25,50,100]}},\"evals\":[],\"jsHooks\":[]}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n</details>\n\nTo calculate the species richness, we measured the total number of species observed in each ejido and added them together for the Project Extent, while excluding any species that was found outside of the tropical/sub-tropical dry forests, as seen in [Table 10](#table10).\n\n<details>\n\n<summary>Table 10. Bird Species Lists by Ejido</summary>\n\n::: {#table10}\n:::\n\n::: terra-table-title\nTable 10. Bird Species Lists by Ejido\n:::\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<div class=\"datatables html-widget html-fill-item\" id=\"htmlwidget-b5e48a6ea12784450bea\" style=\"width:100%;height:auto;\"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-b5e48a6ea12784450bea\">{\"x\":{\"filter\":\"none\",\"vertical\":false,\"data\":[[\"Crypturellus cinnamomeus\",\"Cairina moschata\",\"Ortalis vetula\",\"Penelope purpurascens\",\"Crax rubra\",\"Meleagris ocellata\",\"Patagioenas speciosa\",\"Patagioenas flavirostris\",\"Claravis pretiosa\",\"Leptotila verreauxi\",\"Leptotila jamaicensis\",\"Leptotila plumbeiceps\",\"Dromococcyx phasianellus\",\"Piaya cayana\",\"Coccyzus americanus\",\"Nyctidromus albicollis\",\"Nyctiphrynus yucatanicus\",\"Antrostomus badius\",\"Archilochus colubris\",\"Cynanthus canivetii\",\"Amazilia yucatanensis\",\"Amazilia tzacatl\",\"Chlorestes candida\",\"Aramides albiventris\",\"Coragyps atratus\",\"Cathartes aura\",\"Spizaetus o